<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As far as I can remember, the proposal had support to pass except for France and Germany (who said they'd veto it). So, the point was kind of moot. Why continue with the resolution when a veto power has said that they would unconditionally veto it. Kind of sounds like wasted time/effort. Bush eventually said that we would do it without their support.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually the proposal never got the nine votes it would have required, so they dropped it.  Had it gotten nine votes, yes France would have vetoed it, but it would have been a victory for Bush anyway &quot;Hey, everyone wants to do it, but France is being bleh&quot;.  When they didn't get the nine votes, they dropped asking for it, and France was quick to point out that there was no majority of the SC in support of it.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why is everyone talking about the latest resolution and not the others? I have seen folks talking about the older ones. I don't know why they talk about &quot;only&quot; that one. When they talk about &quot;any means necessary&quot;, which means military force, they are talking about the 1991 resolution as it is the one that authorizes its use.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Bush cites UN Res 1441, not 678, same with Powell, Rumsfield, etc.  They seem to understand something about 678 being not enough to consider this supported by the UN - hence the &quot;we'll do this on our own&quot;.  You can't have both, UN support, and the claim, &quot;we're doing this on our own with a coalition of the willing&quot;.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Of course, we could just sit around and wait until we are sure that Iraq has nuclear weapons along with other WMD, then there would be nothing we could do about it because it would be another nuclear power with an insane, power-mad leader who hates the USA. I don't like war either but I'd rather deal with it now than then.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree with you, under no circumstance should Iraq be allowed to have nukes.  Even with only modest conventional forces he has proven to be too much a maverick for the international community to deal with effectively.  That doesn't mean I don't think we rushed it this time around.<br>
